  "chunk_index": 28,
  "summary": "After Mr. Duns leaves a meeting, Colonel Anderson reveals that Inspector Rice has arranged for two people to watch his house. Poirot expresses confidence that the meticulous \"ABC\" killer will eventually make a mistake. The investigation is interrupted by Mr. Bauer from the Black Swan Hotel, who arrives with a young woman named Mary Stroud.\n\nMary reports an incident occurring around 4:45, when she entered a guest's room to deliver hot water and discovered a man washing his hands in a sink filled with red water. Her employer, Mr. Boll, adds that the man was shirtless and holding a wet sleeve. Mary describes the man as being of medium height, slightly hunched, wearing glasses, a shabby black coat, and a homburg hat. Following this report, a constable retrieves the hotel register, which contains a cramped signature reading \"A.B. Case\" or \"ABC.\" The register also notes that the guest brought a large box filled with silk stockings. Inspector Croome congratulates Poirot, noting that his intuition was correct.\n\nLater, at Scotland Yard, Detective Inspector Croome is visited by Tom Hattinger. Hattinger claims that his girlfriend Lily’s mother rents a room in Camden Town to a man named Castor, whom he describes as a mild-mannered, down-on-his-luck individual. Hattinger notes that Castor had mentioned traveling to Cheltenham and was reportedly in Chester and at the seaside during previous murders. While Lily believes Castor is too harmless to be the killer, Hattinger expresses growing suspicion regarding the man's character.",
